                    <h2>About us </h2>
                    <div class="about-content">
                        <p class="text-justify">

                            Today the world is facing a global issue in the shape of COVID-19 that developed into a pandemic within few days of its outbreak. This outbreak has affected the lives of people to a great extent. In the recent past, pandemics have had more devastating
                            effects, as governments could not predict the potential outbreaks of pandemics which resulted in inefficient preparations given lesser time. Hence, the emergence of the coronavirus pandemic in late 2019 and the lack of research
                            on past pandemics inspired our FYP team to a great extent. Keeping in view the void, we decided to pursue a final year project in this very domain. The vision of our project was to develop a portal for scientists, medical doctors,
                            and researchers to monitor and indicate the potential imminence of pandemics in the future with a strong focus on the correlation among the past zoonotic pandemics. We deployed supervised and unsupervised learning models trained
                            on a unique dataset comprising of genomic, meteorological, and statistical data features onto our interactive web portal. The scope of this project includes more than 500 influenza viruses from the last two decades but we laid
                            primary focus upon SARS 2003, MERS 2012, and COVID-19. The project will be the first of its kind in correlating past zoonotic pandemics in the last two decades to predict the possibilities of spillovers in the future.
                        </p>


